div.p:
And in another place;
Where ſhall I goe, ſhee comes, ſhe's there, I die:


Here the Poet did not ſee the Furies, but he gives ſo lively a repreſentation of them, that he almoſt makes his Auditors believe they do: and though I cannot well ſay how good his Tallent is in expreſſing the other paſſions, yet in thoſe two of Love and Fury (which are his Maſter-piece) he is very excellent; not but that he has a bold ſtroke in many other things. For notwithſtanding his fancy is not naturally high, yet in weighty ſubjects, he ſcrues it up to a Tragical greatneſs; not unjuſtly therefore, may we ſay that of him, which the Poet do's of the Lyon.
